Wuthipong Kachathamakul, also known as Ko Tee, was a Thai political activist and outspoken critic of the monarchy and military. After facing charges of lèse-majesté (insulting the monarchy), he fled to Laos for safety. In 2017, he was abducted from his home near Vientiane by armed men in what is believed to be a forced disappearance. Despite international concern, his fate remains unknown, and Lao authorities have not clarified what happened.

His case highlights the dangers faced by dissidents—even in exile—and how political speech can trigger severe retaliation across borders. Communication methods that avoid exposure, tracking, or storage on centralized servers become crucial in such contexts. Concepts to look deeper into include transnational repression, lèse-majesté laws, forced disappearance, exile surveillance, and secure, decentralized messaging.